<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="159" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="159">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="159">
The specific name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Domenech &amp; Crespo" authorityYear="2020" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Theridion" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="promiscuum" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="promiscuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">promiscuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from the Latin word for 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“intermingling”">&quot;intermingling&quot;</normalizedToken>
, referring to the morphological similarity with other species of the 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. melanurum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="melanurum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. melanurum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. It also makes reference to the possible introgression between this species and other closely related species here reported.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="159" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="159">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="159">
Males of 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. promiscuum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="promiscuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. promiscuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. can be distinguished from other species in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. melanurum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="melanurum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. melanurum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group by a bent and twisted embolus, forming a marked angle (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Theridion promiscuum sp. nov. a) Female paratype MZB 2019 - 1688, dorsal habitus. b) Male paratype MZB 2017 - 3713, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406583" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">5e</figureCitation>
); embolus shorter in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. promiscuum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="promiscuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. promiscuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. than in sympatric 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. mystaceum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="mystaceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. mystaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Theridion mystaceum. a) Female, dorsal habitus b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406584" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">6e</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. harmsi" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="harmsi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. harmsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Theridion harmsi. a) Female, dorsal habitus. b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406585" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">7e</figureCitation>
); tip of the embolus pointing distally in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. promiscuum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="promiscuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. promiscuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Theridion promiscuum sp. nov. a) Female paratype MZB 2019 - 1688, dorsal habitus. b) Male paratype MZB 2017 - 3713, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406583" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">5c</figureCitation>
) and pointing retrolaterally in remaining species (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Theridion mystaceum. a) Female, dorsal habitus b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406584" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">6c</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Theridion harmsi. a) Female, dorsal habitus. b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406585" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">7c</figureCitation>
); base, prolateral part of the embolus more sclerotized in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. promiscuum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="promiscuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. promiscuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Theridion promiscuum sp. nov. a) Female paratype MZB 2019 - 1688, dorsal habitus. b) Male paratype MZB 2017 - 3713, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406583" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">5e</figureCitation>
) than in remaining species of the 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. melanurum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="melanurum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. melanurum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Theridion mystaceum. a) Female, dorsal habitus b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406584" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">6e</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Theridion harmsi. a) Female, dorsal habitus. b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406585" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">7e</figureCitation>
); presence of small barbs in embolus base distal border is unique to 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. promiscuum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="promiscuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. promiscuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (only visible in SEM; Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Scanning electron microscope image of left male palp. Top: ventral view. Bottom: prolateral view. a, b) Theridion promiscuum sp. nov. c, d) Theridion mystaceum. e, f) Theridion harmsi. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406586" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">8a, b</figureCitation>
). Females of 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. promiscuum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="promiscuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. promiscuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. mystaceum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="mystaceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. mystaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. harmsi" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="harmsi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. harmsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the lower position of copulatory duct openings in atrium in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. promiscuum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="promiscuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. promiscuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Theridion promiscuum sp. nov. a) Female paratype MZB 2019 - 1688, dorsal habitus. b) Male paratype MZB 2017 - 3713, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406583" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">5f</figureCitation>
), which are central in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. harmsi" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="harmsi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. harmsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Theridion harmsi. a) Female, dorsal habitus. b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406585" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">7f</figureCitation>
) and close to or under lateral walls of atrium in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. mystaceum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="mystaceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. mystaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Theridion mystaceum. a) Female, dorsal habitus b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406584" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">6f</figureCitation>
); copulatory ducts shorter, fewer coils in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. promiscuum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="promiscuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. promiscuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Theridion promiscuum sp. nov. a) Female paratype MZB 2019 - 1688, dorsal habitus. b) Male paratype MZB 2017 - 3713, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406583" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">5g</figureCitation>
) than in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. mystaceum" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="mystaceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. mystaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Theridion mystaceum. a) Female, dorsal habitus b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406584" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">6g</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. harmsi" pageId="0" pageNumber="159" rank="species" species="harmsi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">T. harmsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Theridion harmsi. a) Female, dorsal habitus. b) Male, dorsal habitus. c) Left male palp, ventral. d) Left male palp, retrolateral e) Male embolus f) Female epigynum, ventral g) Female vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (a, b); 0.1 mm (c, d, f, g); 0.05 mm (e)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.49946.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/406585" pageId="0" pageNumber="159">7g</figureCitation>
